You get the required behaviour easily by using [flex][1]. The [flex-wrap][2] propery will take care of adjusting the items inside the container.

So, when you have small screen device, `flex-wrap` will move the items those overflows to a new `row`. Hence, we use [flex-grow][3] to tell the items to grow based on the space available.

And the [flex-basis][4] will tell the items to limit the minimun `width` it can shrink. 

Here is the working example.
&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: false babel: null --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

.box-container {
        height: 150px;
        display: flex;
        flex-wrap: wrap;
    }
.box{
  display: flex;
  flex-grow: 1;
  flex-basis: 150px;
    
}
.box:nth-child(odd) {
  background-color: lightblue;
  border: 1px solid #000;
}

.box:nth-child(even) {
  background-color: aquamarine;
  border: 1px solid #000;
}


